{"id":"1404.7713","submitter":"Jos\\'e Luis Romero","authors":"Lu\\'is Daniel Abreu, Karlheinz Gr\\\"ochenig and Jos\\'e Luis Romero","title":"On accumulated spectrograms","comments":"21 pages, 3 figures","journal-ref":"Transactions of the American Mathematical Society, Vol.368 No.5,\n  (2016) p.3629 - 3649","doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CA math.FA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We study the eigenvalues and eigenfunctions of the time-frequency\nlocalization operator $H_\\Omega$ on a domain $\\Omega$ of the time-frequency\nplane. The eigenfunctions are the appropriate prolate spheroidal functions for\nan arbitrary domain $\\Omega$. Indeed, in analogy to the classical theory of\nLandau-Slepian-Pollak, the number of eigenvalues of $H_\\Omega$ in $[1-\\delta ,\n1]$ is equal to the measure of $\\Omega$ up to an error term depending on the\nperimeter of the boundary of $\\Omega$. Our main results show that the\nspectrograms of the eigenfunctions corresponding to the large eigenvalues\n(which we call the accumulated spectrogram) form an approximate partition\nofunity of the given domain $\\Omega $. We derive both asymptotic,\nnon-asymptotic, and weak $L^2$ error estimates for the accumulated spectrogram.\nAs a consequence the domain $\\Omega$ can be approximated solely from the\nspectrograms of eigenfunctions without information about their phase.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 30 Apr 2014 13:09:55 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 15 Jul 2014 12:43:00 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-03-29"}
